{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17642969","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17642969"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T19:48:08+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T19:48:08+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17977"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"17977","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/17977"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10691"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"77654"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"10691","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/10691"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17977"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"63167"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4940"},{"type":"tags","id":"4943"},{"type":"tags","id":"11220"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"24894"},{"type":"contributions","id":"24897"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"77654","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/77654"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003E\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following functional groups is typically introduced or unmasked during a phase 1 reaction in xenobiotic metabolism?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Hydroxyl","Acetyl","Glucuronyl","Sulphate","Amino"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EPhase 1 reactions in xenobiotic metabolism involve the introduction or unmasking of functional groups, such as a \u003Cstrong\u003Ehydroxyl\u003C/strong\u003E group, through processes like oxidation, reduction, or hydrolysis. These reactions are primarily catalysed by cytochrome P450 enzymes, which play a crucial role in drug metabolism.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAcetyl\u003C/strong\u003E groups are typically added during phase 2 reactions, which involve conjugation to increase water solubility for excretion.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EGlucuronyl\u003C/strong\u003E groups are also added during phase 2 reactions, specifically in glucuronidation, a major pathway for drug conjugation.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESulphate\u003C/strong\u003E groups are added during phase 2 reactions in a process known as sulphation, which also aids in drug excretion.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAmino\u003C/strong\u003E groups are not typically introduced during phase 1 reactions; they may be involved in phase 2 reactions, such as amino acid conjugation.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Phase 1 reactions in xenobiotic metabolism typically involve the introduction or unmasking of a functional group, such as a hydroxyl group, through oxidation, reduction, or hydrolysis.","These reactions are primarily catalysed by cytochrome P450 enzymes, which play a crucial role in drug metabolism."],"references":["Gilbert-Barness, E., Barness, L. A., \u0026 Farrell, P. M. (Eds.). (2017). Metabolic diseases: foundations of clinical management, genetics, and pathology. IOS Press","Lanham-New, S. A., Macdonald, I. A., \u0026 Roche, H. M. (Eds.). (2011). Nutrition and metabolism. John Wiley \u0026 Sons","Roche, H. M., Macdonald, I. A., Schols, A. M., \u0026 Lanham-New, S. A. (Eds.). (2024). Nutrition and metabolism. John Wiley \u0026 Sons","Omiecinski CJ, Vanden Heuvel JP, Perdew GH, Peters JM. Xenobiotic metabolism, disposition, and regulation by receptors: from biochemical phenomenon to predictors of major toxicities. Toxicol Sci. 2011 Mar;120 Suppl 1(Suppl 1):S49-75. doi: 10.1093/toxsci/kfq338. Epub 2010 Nov 8. PMID: 21059794; PMCID: PMC3145385"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"63167"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17977"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"63167","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/63167"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-01-07T21:06:02+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-01-08T00:06:45+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10691"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"77654"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"74","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/74"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level I","synonyms":null,"description":"Remember (identifying and retrieving information)","position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"7"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"4940","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/4940"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udee7","name":"Cell Biology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":"2024-10-17T23:16:52+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-10-31T13:16:21+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"14"}}